<DIV class=3Dinteract id=3Dinteract_ou_119></DIV>
<P>OpenOffice.org 2.0 is finally out with much fanfare, but is it a =
memory and=20
resource hog?&nbsp; This is what I was wondering when I did <A=20
href=3D"http://blogs.zdnet.com/Ou/?p=3D101">this shootout</A> last month =
between=20
Microsoft Excel 2003 and OpenOffice.org 1.1.4 Calc.&nbsp; The backers =
of&nbsp;=20
OpenOffice.org immediately complained that I didn=E2=80=99t test their =
new=20
OpenOffice.org Beta2.&nbsp; I immediately added the Beta2 results, and =
then the=20
backers of OpenOffice.org complained that I was comparing Beta software =
to=20
production software.&nbsp; Now that OpenOffice.org 2.0 is finally out, =
I=E2=80=99ve put=20
it to the test again to see if the shipping version really makes a=20
difference.</P>
<P><STRONG>File creation and file load times for Excel and =
Calc:</STRONG></P>
<TABLE height=3D144 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D3 width=3D375 =
border=3D1>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD>&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>Calc 2.0 =
ODS</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>Calc 2.0 =
SXC</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>Excel 2003 =
XLS</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>Excel 2003 =
XML</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>Excel 2003 ZIP =
XML</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD><FONT size=3D2>Create</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>179 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>184 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>1 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>13 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>18 =
sec</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD><FONT size=3D2>Load</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>141 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>161 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>2 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>38 sec</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>47 =
sec</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD><FONT size=3D2>RAM used</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>234,496 =
KB</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT size=3D2>232,932 =
KB</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT =
size=3D2>89,164<BR>KB</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT =
size=3D2>41,980<BR>KB</FONT></TD>
    <TD align=3Dright width=3D"17%"><FONT =
size=3D2>NA</FONT></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
<P><FONT size=3D2><STRONG>Note:</STRONG> ZIP XML isn=E2=80=99t an actual =
file format, it=E2=80=99s=20
just a zipped Microsoft XML file.&nbsp; The next version of Office 12 =
will use a=20
compressed XML format so ZIP XML is meant to simulate compressed =
XML.&nbsp;=20
Since SXC and ODS are compressed XML formats, this also makes the =
comparison=20
times fair.&nbsp; You can download this compressed&nbsp;<A=20
href=3D"http://www.lanarchitect.net/Examples/200264-l.zip">16-sheet =
MS-XML=20
file</A> and run the tests on your own.&nbsp; OpenOffice.org users can =
download=20
this <A href=3D"http://www.lanarchitect.net/Examples/200264-l.sxc"=20
target=3D_self>16-sheet SXC</A> if they just want to test OpenOffice.org =
Calc=20
performance.&nbsp; Both files have identical data.</FONT></P>
<P>As you can see, OpenOffice.org and XML in general is extremely slow =
compared=20
to the native Microsoft XLS binary file format.&nbsp; Not only is it =
slow, it=20
also chews up the CPU.&nbsp; My computer happens to be a 3.4 GHz hyper =
threaded=20
processor and the physical CPU was being taxed at 100% during the 2 to 3 =
minutes=20
it took to open the OpenOffice.org Open Document files.&nbsp; Had this =
been a=20
lesser CPU, the file load and creation times would have been much =
lower.</P>
<P>The other big issue is how much RAM OpenOffice.org Calc takes to have =
the=20
exact same data loaded as Microsoft Excel.&nbsp; OpenOffice.org is =
clearly a CPU=20
and Memory hog.&nbsp; To get an idea of how much memory the entire=20
OpenOffice.org suite takes, I did this memory footprint comparison of =
all the=20
Office applications.</P>
<P><STRONG>Memory requirements of base application (no data =
load):</STRONG></P>
<TABLE height=3D236 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D3 width=3D375 =
border=3D1>
  <TBODY>
